<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHERN SECTION GIRLS BASKETBALL; 
</P>
<P>
LOS ALTOS ADVANCES, 64-56 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Altos, the No. 3-seeded team in the Southern Section Girls 4-A Division, 
defeated Coachella Valley Thursday night, 64-56, in a first-round playoff game 
at Los Altos High. 
</P>
<P>
Susan Peters, a 5-foot-11 senior forward who has signed a national letter of 
intent with USC in volleyball, led the Conquerors (25-1) with 25 points, 12 
rebounds and 10 assists. Peters is averaging 22 points and 12 rebounds overall. 
</P>
<P>
Jenny Valenzuela, averaging 22 points a game for Coachella Valley (12-8), was 
held to 13 points. In other first-round playoff games: 
</P>
<P>
Montclair 53, El Monte 51 -- Montclair's Nika Dunn sank one of two free throws 
with four seconds left to break a 51-51 tie in the 5-A Division game at El 
Monte. El Monte (16-9) then turned the ball over when one of its players 
stepped out of bounds. Lorena Gonzalez, a Montclair junior varsity player who 
was brought up for the playoffs, was intentionally fouled with one second 
remaining. She made one of two free throws. Montclair is 13-11. 
</P>
<P>
Downey 64, San Clemente 49 -- Downey (18-7), an at-Large entry from the San 
Gabriel Valley League, outscored San Clemente (18-7) to win their 4-AA division 
game at Downey High. After a competitive first half which ended, 31-29, Downey 
pulled ahead to a 45-39 lead at the end of the third quarter. Heidi Crammer, 
who led Downey with 20 points, scored six of her points in the fourth quarter 
to ensure the win. 
</P>
<P>
Santa Ynez 62, Kern Valley 55 -- Santa Ynez (17-5), the third-seeded team in 
the 2-A Division, opened a 17-0 lead and was never threatened. Amy Kisling, 
5-11 junior forward, led the Pirates with 27 points and 11 rebounds. Crossroads 
60, Whitney 58 -- Jamila Banks scored 34 points and had 13 rebounds to lead the 
Roadrunners (20-2) to a 2-A Division overtime win at Santa Monica High. Banks 
scored all six points in overtime on a fast-break basket, a jump shot and a 
10-foot shot with 23 seconds remaining. 
</P>
</TEXT>
